🧠 First principle (don’t skip this)
Source files (.cpp) → must be listed → compiled
Header files (.h/.hpp) → optional to list → only for IDE visibility

CMake does not need headers to build, but you often include them anyway.

🧱 Method 1 — Directly list multiple source files (baseline)

This is the simplest and most correct starting point.

add_executable(MyProj
    main.cpp
    foo.cpp
    bar.cpp
)

👉 This is:

explicit
predictable
recommended for small/medium projects
Adding headers (optional)

add_executable(MyProj
    main.cpp
    foo.cpp
    foo.hpp
)

👉 This:

does NOT affect compilation
just helps IDEs (CLion, VSCode, etc.)
🧱 Method 2 — Split sources using variables

set(SOURCES
    main.cpp
    foo.cpp
)

add_executable(MyProj ${SOURCES})

👉 Why use this?

cleaner when the list gets long
reusable across targets

⚠️ Limitation:

still manual listing
variables don’t add real structure
🧱 Method 3 — target_sources() (modern, scalable)

Instead of stuffing everything into add_executable, you attach sources later:

add_executable(MyProj)

target_sources(MyProj
    PRIVATE
        main.cpp
        foo.cpp
)

👉 Why this is powerful:

lets you incrementally build targets
useful when splitting across multiple CMake files
🧱 Method 4 — Folder-based using file(GLOB ...) ⚠️

file(GLOB SOURCES "src/*.cpp")

add_executable(MyProj ${SOURCES})

👉 This auto-includes all .cpp files in a folder.

❗ Why people warn against this

CMake won’t automatically re-run when new files are added.

So:

you add new.cpp
build fails or ignores it
you must re-run CMake manually
Safer version (still not perfect)
file(GLOB SOURCES CONFIGURE_DEPENDS "src/*.cpp")

👉 This tells CMake:

“Re-scan when files change”

Still:

slightly slower
less explicit than manual listing
🧱 Method 5 — File sets (modern CMake 3.23+ / 4.x)

This is what you mentioned—file sets are the “new clean way.”

target_sources(MyProj
    PRIVATE
        FILE_SET my_sources
        TYPE CXX_SOURCES
        FILES
            main.cpp
            foo.cpp
)
For headers (this is where file sets shine)

target_sources(MyProj
    PUBLIC
        FILE_SET HEADERS
        BASE_DIRS include
        FILES
            include/foo.hpp
)

👉 Why this matters:

clean separation of headers vs sources
required for proper installation/exporting
modern replacement for messy include handling
🧱 Method 6 — Split into libraries (REAL scaling method)

Instead of “linking folders,” you should do this:

add_library(core
    src/foo.cpp
)

target_include_directories(core PUBLIC include)

add_executable(MyProj main.cpp)

target_link_libraries(MyProj PRIVATE core)

👉 This is how real projects scale:

each folder = library
then link them
❌ What you cannot do (common misconceptions)
❌ “Link a folder directly”

You cannot do:

add_executable(MyProj src/)

CMake doesn’t treat folders as build units.

❌ “Automatically include everything safely”

There is no perfect auto-include-all-files system without tradeoffs.

You must choose between:

explicit listing ✅ (recommended)
globbing ⚠️ (convenient, less safe)
❌ Headers being compiled

Headers:

are not compiled
are pulled in via #include
🧠 When to use what
Small project

→ direct listing

Medium project

→ target_sources() + variables

Large project

→ split into libraries

Experimental / fast iteration

→ GLOB CONFIGURE_DEPENDS

Modern packaging / install

→ file sets
